The paper deals with the problem of identifying distinct social contexts in a graph, which is a common topic in social network analysis. Therefore, cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.SOC (Social and Information Networks) are the most likely categories. The paper also proposes a novel notation of discriminative core, which involves graph theory and algorithms, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a likely category as well. The proposed algorithm for top-k search involves pruning techniques, which is a common technique in database systems, making cs.DB (Databases) a possible category. Finally, the paper presents experimental results to verify the superiority of the proposed method, which falls under the category of cs.LG (Machine Learning).
